               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18341205-name-163" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18341205-name-163" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341205-name-163" type="surname" value="CLAMP"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341205-name-163" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES CLAMP</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Church-entry, St. Ann's, Blackfriars. On the 4th of December, I was coming along Aldgate, about half-past seven o'clock—there was a little shuffling in the street—I turned my head, and the officer had got my handkerchief, and the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18341205-name-164" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18341205-name-164" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341205-name-164" type="surname" value="BRACKLEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18341205-name-164" type="given" value="SIMEON"></interp>SIMEON BRACKLEY</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a watchman. On my way through Aldgate, about half-past seven o'clock, I saw the prisoner follow the prosecutor from Duke-street to Mitre-street, where the Stratford coaches collect—the prosecutor tried to get through—I saw the prisoner lift his pocket, and draw the handkerchief—I collared him, and he dropped it at his feet—my fellow-watchman picked it up, and the prosecutor claimed it.</p>
